climbs.name: Whipperly Wamberly Walk
climbs.fa: Porter Jarrard, Andy Otis, and Frank Dusl

content.description: A stout lesson on climbing quick on smaller holds.  WWW ascends a first small roof on descent holds which peter out, leaving one choice: crank on the crimp at the lip and keep on cruising.  The middle face climbs smoothly up the the final roof, a bit pumpy, but generally big pockets and gymnastic roof climbing. A fun line.
content.location: Located on the left side of the Hardware wall before the Fallen Idol pillar.  Locate the lower small roof at the 2nd clip and the bigger bulging roof higher on the route.

content.description: Just to the right of Mark 13, shared first two bolts with Mark 13 and then travels up and right joining Angry Bob's last three bolts, technical gold rock.  A little sporty up top (5.10).
Deep pockets, huge hueccos, and a small sharp hold or 2 define this route. Decent movement throughout, on somewhat softer orange/peanut butter colored rock.
content.location: Starts 15 feet right of No Left Ear.  If you don’t know that reference 100 feet right that giant pillar leaning against the wall, look for a black steak coming out of a large huecco at 3/4 height.

content.description: This has engaging climbing.
content.location:
It is just right of

Fluffy Bagel

.

content.description: Disgusting, greasy direct start to Hardware (to the right in brown rock)  Joins Hardware at bolt 4.  Try Jill instead.

climbs.name: Shades
climbs.fa: Porter Jarrard, Hassan Saab, Frank Dusl

content.description: Crimpy climbing on small holds up a just slightly more than vertical face.  Harder for shorties (but hey, what isn't?).

This burly extension pierces the obvious high roof above "No Left Ear".  The boulder problem is quick and dirty but nothing to sneeze at.

Climb "No Left Ear" to the alcove below the roof, then move out to the lip utilizing a pair of sloping pockets.  Grope over the lip for a hard-to-find pocket, then make desparate reaches to a set of big, incut edges, throw a foot onto the lip (but which one?), then pull onto the raspy slab.
content.protection: Many bolts to 2BA with fixed biners, then 2 more bolts to a poor anchor that is sure to twist the heck out of your rope.  Best to move left to the WWW anchor and lower off that.
content.location: Continue in the Z-axis from the anchor of No Left Ear.  No Left Ear is the third bolted line right of the leaning pillar.

content.description: Thin start leads to open-handed climbing up an arête.  Originally rated 5.11d, but we'll see what the consensus is.  This climb could easily be combined with the upper section of Mutt and Jeff.
content.location: Located just right of Mutt and Jeff, this climb follows the arête on the left side of the obvious pillar feature.

content.description:
This fantastic line is a great choice for a warmup, or for anyone looking for a moderate jughaul.  The big flakes & huecos that grace this wall are a nice break from the sharp crimps and tiny pockets found nearby.

Begin by cruising jutting flakes up and right.  When the flakes run out, follow big pockets back left to a distinct crux move left from an obvious sidepull.  Above, the line slabs out below the big roof.
content.protection: 8-9 bolts to Clip-n-Lower anchors. An extension continues over the high roof at 5.11+/12-.
content.location: The next bolted line right of WWW, or the third line right of the leaning pillar.

content.description: Easier version of Heaven Can Wait.  Start with the Heaven pillar, climbing straight up (instead of left for 'Heaven can Wait 11b').  Fun steep climbing similar but slightly easier than HCW.  For a harder start do 'Postcards from the Edge', the 5.11+ slappy arete start and continue up Mutt and Jeff.
content.location: On the right side of the wall starting with the detached flake and following up the face above.

climbs.name: Mo
climbs.fa: Porter Jarrard, Hassan Saab, Frank Dusl

content.description: Two routes left of Hardware.  Crimpy sequences and sustained climbing.  Getting between bolt 3 and 4 is the crux with a flat left sidepull and crappy feet to some smallish crimps out right.  There is also a redpoint crux up high trending left and clipping the last bolt.  Hard for 12b.

A quiet classic.  First 3 bolt get dirty every spring run off don’t be scared take 5 minuted to stick clip up and brush that shit we’ll thank you all winter.  Thin start leads to a low crux involving either side pulles or gastons.  Leaving bolt 4 is nothing but overhanging 5.11 glory, possibly the best in in canyon and it goes on for somthing like 7-9 clips.  Expect a spot of choss after the last bolt... can be avoided if you cowboy up and own that mono in the better stone it is a 5.12 after all.
Just to the right of Hardware, twin cracks of sorts, good and technical, guidebook says .13a; you be the judge.

climbs.name: Jill
climbs.fa: Porter Jarrard, Frank Dusl, Hassan Saab

content.description: Hard, crimpy boulder problem start to less hard but still crimpy climbing.  Not a bad route, but not a classic.

Just to the right of Postcards.  Climb right side of detached pillar and then onto face.  Face crux low to jugs and pockets.  Rest below upper headwall and throw some big moves on the way to the anchor (crux).  Could be dusty.  Needs more traffic.
content.location: Just to the right of Postcards from the Edge.  Right side of the detached pillar then onto face.

content.description: Direct start to Heaven Can Wait.  Do a sick crimpy boulder problem for 3 bolts, followed by 2 bolts of less difficult but still pumpy climbing.  The route joins HCW after bolt 5 and finishes there.  Start with bolt one and 2 stick clipped as the first bolt is really a directional to keep you from getting dental flossed on the first difficult moves.

A little laybacking, a little chimneying, a little stemming, followed by a whole bunch of fun pocket pulling make for a wonderful climb.  Does your chalkbag spin?  Be careful not to dump it after you layback the initial flake and stuff your body behind the flake.  At the top of the flake, leave its security with a left traverse on pockets.  Several clips of vertical pocket pulling are followed by the bulging, brilliant, pumpy and stout 11- crux right before the chains.
content.location: On the right side of the Hardware wall, climbs the left side of the obvious detached flake before heading up the face.

content.description: Just steeper than vertical.  Climbing Hardware you'll pull on good crimps and great pockets. Hardware starts off with interesting and stout climbing past the first two bolts followed by the crux passing the 3rd bolt. The line moves right and finishes on easy but pumpy pocket pulling.
content.location: Located in the middle of the wall, the furthest right of the middle lines that starts on a seam of sorts.  Hardware is also identifiable by the thin, less traveled, 3 bolt direct start called Software (12c).

content.description: Scramble up to ledge to clip first bolt. Crux b/w bolts 2-4. Bigger pockets above.
content.location: Just right of the fallen idol pillar. 10' left of Apple City Quickstep.

content.description: Thin climbing through first 2 bolts gives way to pockets above.
Starts up right trending rail to heinous boulder problem.  Finishes out on pleasant, easier terrain.
content.location: Left of shrubberies at the base of the cliff, this climb is the first climb right of the The Toaster.  It is easily identifiable by a right-slanting rail at the start.

content.description: Steeper climbing on good holds in upper section.
content.location: Just right of Unbreakable and left of Fluffy Bagel

content.description: This climb was resurrected by Scott Robertson, and is now really enjoyable.  Start on a ramp, continuing up good pockets and sidepulls.  There are bolts just below the roof, with the climb to this point feeling like 11b.  There is then a three bolt extension that pulls the roof and feels 11+ (may be height-dependent).
content.location: About 10-15 feet right of the pillar leaning against the wall (Billy Idol).  Look for an obvious ramp and begin on the right side of this.

content.description: just to the left of Mergatroid, technical for a few bolts and then backs off up higher, worth a climb if you need a fix
Sustained pockets and flakes lead to easier climbing before a roof crux.
content.location: This climb is currently the third bolt line to the right of the leaning pillar (Billy Idol).  Pulls through a large roof.
